name: Control of Respiration
question1: Describe the control of respiration.  Name the four groups/centres (4).
contents:
Ventilation is controlled by:

The respiratory centre is located in the brainstem and is composed of a group of nuclei within the medulla and pons.

1) Dorsal respiratory group in medulla = inspiratory neurons

  • Controls diaphragm
  • Normal tidal inspiration

2) Ventral respiratory group in medulla = inspiratory and expiratory neurons

  • Controls intercostals
  • Forced expiration
  • Pre-Botzinger complex = respiratory pacemaker

3) Apneustic centre in lower pons = modifies DRG neurons to prevent over expansion

  • Ablation = apneusis = pathologically long, deep breaths

4) Pneumotaxic centre in upper pons = modifies DRG neurons to reduce depth of inspiration

  • Modulates respiratory pattern, can increase RR
question2: Name the chemoreceptors affecting the control of ventilation.  (2) categories.
question3: Describe some other receptors controlling ventilation.
contents3:
• (3) Arterial baroreceptors
  • Aortic or carotid sinus baroreceptor sense increased BP = respiratory depression
  • If sense decreased BP = respiratory stimulation
  • (4) Pulmonary stretch receptors in bronchial SM
  • Reduce depth of inspiration
  • Afferents to apneustic centre via vagus nerve = Hering-Breuer reflex 
  • (5) Irritant receptors in airway epithelium
  • Cause bronchoconstriction and stimulate ventilation in presence of noxious substances
  • (6) Juxtacapillary receptors = non-myelinated C fibres in alveolar walls
  • Activation = increased ventilation, bradycardia, hypotension, dyspnoea
  • (7) Stimulated by pulmonary oedema and emboli
  • (8) Muscle spindles = increase ventilatory response during exercise
  • (9) Pain receptors = increased ventilation
  • (10) Thalamus = increased core body temp = raised ventilation
  • (11) Limbic system = extreme emotional states can cause hyperventilation
  • (12) Cerebral cortex = can override, but reach break point when hypoxaemia or hypercapnoea overrides voluntary control
question4: Describe the effects of raised CO2 on the body?
contents4:
Hypercarbia stimulates respiration via activation of peripheral and central chemoreceptors

Graphs

MV vs PaO2

Minute ventilation versus alveolar oxygen partial pressure.

  • At PACO2 of 5kPa the line should demonstrate that, under normal conditions the MV remains relatively constant around 6 l.min-1. Until the PaO2 falls below 8kPa. (Illustrates the hypoxic drive so often talked about in COPD)
  • At PACO2 of 10kPa this line is plotted above and to the right of the first and demonstrates the effect of a coexisting hypercarbia on hypoxic ventilatory drive.


MV vs PaO2

Minute ventilation verus alveolar carbon dioxide partial pressure

  • Normal:
  • Plot a normal PACO2 (5kPa) at a normal MV (6L min-1).
  • If the PACO2 is doubled, the MV increases four-fold in a linear fashion.
  • Above 10-11kPa, the line should fall away representing depression of respiration with very high PACO2. A the lower end of the line, the curve also flattens and does not reach zero on either axis.
  • Raised threshold:
  • Plot a second parallel curve to the right of the first.
  • Reduced sensitivity:
  • plot a third curve with shallower gradient.
  • This represents decreased sensitivity such that a greater increment in PACO2 is required in order to achieve the same increment in MV. Also seen with opiates.
question5: Draw a graph that demonstrates the effect that ventilation has on PACO2
contents5:

As MV doubles , so the PACO2 halves - the curve is therefore a rectangular hperbola.

Begin by plotting a normal PACO2 (5kPa) at normal MV (6 L.min-1)


Voluntary control of respiration

The peripheral and chemoreceptors are important in controlling involuntary respiration

Voluntary control includes :

  • Cerebral cortex - which can override brainstem control within limits. eg voluntary hyperventilation
  • Limbic system and hypothalamus - emotion such as rage and fear also alter respiratory system
